WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:03.200
Okay, we are on time now, so thank you very much for coming.

2
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:07.040
This is very late in the day, and I am the only thing between you and dinner,

3
00:00:07.780 --> 00:00:10.180
so I'm trying to keep it entertaining.

4
00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:11.380
And

5
00:00:12.340 --> 00:00:16.320
there is a QR code that was shown where people can

6
00:00:16.380 --> 00:00:19.680
ask questions by message or the app.

7
00:00:20.820 --> 00:00:21.460
Okay, so

8
00:00:22.420 --> 00:00:26.100
the first thing I wanted to disclose is that I don't consider myself an

9
00:00:26.180 --> 00:00:30.060
expert. So the expert session may not be the best

10
00:00:30.160 --> 00:00:34.040
title, but I'm basically communicating what I learned from people in the

11
00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:37.980
lab and collaborators, and I'll try to bring that up during the

12
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.720
presentation. And the topic is basically trying to

13
00:00:41.780 --> 00:00:45.430
exploit defective tumor immune cell interactions, and I

14
00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:49.080
hope I convince you that there is a whole environment

15
00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:52.960
here that can be modulated. And these are my disclosures.

16
00:00:54.449 --> 00:00:58.340
So arguably, the most relevant interaction between cancer cells and

17
00:00:58.380 --> 00:01:01.280
immune cells is the HLA-TCR interaction.

18
00:01:02.100 --> 00:01:05.160
And this is shown here. You can see here this is the invariant chain and the

19
00:01:05.640 --> 00:01:09.360
variant chain. And then basically what happens is that peptides,

20
00:01:09.740 --> 00:01:13.660
usually short nine amino acid long peptides, are presented from the cancer

21
00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:17.000
cell recognized by the TCR, and this basically is the

22
00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:20.520
foundation of adaptive immune response where T cells can

23
00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:25.080
do their job. And for many, many

24
00:01:25.200 --> 00:01:29.080
years it's been established that this pathway can be defective

25
00:01:29.140 --> 00:01:32.440
in cancer. I think a prototype of that is the

26
00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:35.980
downregulation of beta-2 microglobulin, which is this invariant chain, which is

27
00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:38.380
necessary to stabilize peptides.

28
00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:42.820
And this is a paper we published many years ago now where we found that in patients

29
00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:46.820
with acquired resistance to checkpoint blockade, in this case dual checkpoint

30
00:01:46.880 --> 00:01:50.520
blockade, we could see a biallelic loss of the beta-2m

31
00:01:50.530 --> 00:01:53.340
locus. This is chromosome 15, and this is the baseline biopsy.

32
00:01:53.380 --> 00:01:57.250
You can see nothing going on in acquired resistant lesion, that there was

33
00:01:57.300 --> 00:01:59.880
a biallelic loss of beta-2 microglobulin.

34
00:02:00.570 --> 00:02:04.140
We confirmed that using protein analysis, and you can see here the cancer cells are

35
00:02:04.180 --> 00:02:07.440
green, and the cancer cell lost beta-2 microglobulin,

36
00:02:08.081 --> 00:02:10.539
consistent with the lack of the gene.

37
00:02:11.500 --> 00:02:15.180
And then Katie Politi in our institution modeled that in mice, and we could see

38
00:02:15.220 --> 00:02:19.109
that just removal of beta-2m from the cancer cell was sufficient to

39
00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:23.000
confer resistance to PD-1 inhibitors in a carcinogen-induced mouse

40
00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:26.640
model. So we have very strong evidence that beta-2m

41
00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:29.960
downregulation can happen in human tumors, and it can mediate

42
00:02:30.420 --> 00:02:31.840
resistance to immunotherapy.

43
00:02:33.980 --> 00:02:37.540
But I think that the most important concept here is that the antigen presentation

44
00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:41.420
pathway is much bigger than just beta-2 microglobulin. It's quite complex.

45
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:45.989
And what I'm showing here, the HLA class one pathway referred to as APM for

46
00:02:46.040 --> 00:02:49.800
antigen presentation machinery, is actually a sequential

47
00:02:50.660 --> 00:02:53.920
set of steps where antigens are generally generated at the

48
00:02:53.960 --> 00:02:57.100
immunoproteasome by these three proteins, PSMB 8, 9 and 10.

49
00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:01.780
And then those peptides, once they're generated, they're processed by peptidases,

50
00:03:01.940 --> 00:03:05.640
usually amino peptidases. And then from the cytosol, were

51
00:03:05.680 --> 00:03:07.300
generally degraded very quickly.

52
00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:11.620
They are internalized into the endoplasmic reticulum

53
00:03:11.660 --> 00:03:15.520
via the TAP transporter, which is formed by these two proteins, TAP 1 and

54
00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:19.160
TAP 2. And then after the peptides have been loaded onto the

55
00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:22.880
ER, they're loaded onto the HLA by this protein loading

56
00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:26.480
complex formed by tapasin, calreticulin, calnexin, ERP57.

57
00:03:27.380 --> 00:03:31.160
And then after that, they're conjugated with beta-2m and then transferred to the

58
00:03:31.220 --> 00:03:35.210
membrane. So the point I want to make is that this pathway is complex, and

59
00:03:35.240 --> 00:03:39.040
things can go wrong beyond beta-2 microglobulin, and I will

60
00:03:39.100 --> 00:03:42.960
show you some examples of that. Now, at least in theory, in

61
00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.900
the absence of a proficient antigen presentation, T cells will not be

62
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.570
able to recognize cancer cells, and this could obviously be a

63
00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:51.020
problem.

64
00:03:52.320 --> 00:03:56.040
So in the first part of this presentation, I will focus on work done in my

65
00:03:56.120 --> 00:03:59.020
lab, where we have looked at the entire pathway.

66
00:03:59.100 --> 00:04:02.080
We have been dissecting out alterations in the whole pathway.

67
00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:06.280
But today we will focus on TAP 1 and TAP 2 and how the

68
00:04:06.420 --> 00:04:09.860
downregulation of these proteins can affect cancer cell

69
00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:11.200
recognition by T cells.

70
00:04:12.560 --> 00:04:15.920
As an introduction, this TAP transporter is a

71
00:04:15.980 --> 00:04:19.440
heterodimeric transporter formed by TAP 1 and TAP 2, and this is a

72
00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:22.120
cartoon showing the expected structure.

73
00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:26.180
There is an ATP binding domain in the internal part of the ER and

74
00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:30.160
a pore-forming domain. And this is basically where the peptides generated by the

75
00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:33.600
proteasome are shuttled into the ER to be loaded onto the HLA.

76
00:04:34.320 --> 00:04:38.300
At least conceptually, the current notion is that these

77
00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:42.400
proteins are equally represented, and they're expressed in most nucleated

78
00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:46.380
cells. Without this, there shouldn't be a

79
00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:48.260
proper presentation of antigens.

80
00:04:49.780 --> 00:04:53.660
So the first thing we did to query this, we validated assays to look at

81
00:04:53.700 --> 00:04:56.880
this reliably. And this is an example of a human lung cancer.

82
00:04:57.510 --> 00:05:00.100
And what you're seeing in green are the cancer cells.

83
00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:04.200
What you're seeing in blue are the non-cancer cells, what we call stroma or

84
00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:07.500
non-tumor cells, from the same case.

85
00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:11.980
And then TAP 1 is shown in red, TAP 2 is shown in yellow, and CD8 T cells

86
00:05:12.020 --> 00:05:15.960
are shown in white. And one thing that stands out, particularly from

87
00:05:15.980 --> 00:05:19.969
this case, is that if you see the cancer cells, again, shown here in green, they

88
00:05:20.120 --> 00:05:23.740
lack expression of TAP 2, while the non-cancer cells, they

89
00:05:23.780 --> 00:05:27.340
express normal levels. And this is what we call cancer cell selective

90
00:05:27.350 --> 00:05:31.140
downregulation. You can see that TAP 1 is not downregulated in the

91
00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:34.920
cancer cell. Now, there are a few other things to note, for example, that the

92
00:05:34.980 --> 00:05:38.940
only cells that are positive in the cancer cell region are actually CD8 T cells,

93
00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:42.840
but there are very few CD8 T cells in this tumor.

94
00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:46.780
And I'll go back to that, because this absence of T cells is

95
00:05:46.860 --> 00:05:49.940
not fundamentally explained by a lack of antigen.

96
00:05:50.440 --> 00:05:53.780
Suggests that there is something else going on, and I will come back.

97
00:05:55.060 --> 00:05:57.700
So now when we look at this at scale, we screened

98
00:05:57.960 --> 00:06:01.700
819 tumors. These are all treatment-naive tumors, so

99
00:06:01.740 --> 00:06:04.040
even before seeing any treatment, including

100
00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:07.572
immunotherapy.And what we can see is that

101
00:06:07.732 --> 00:06:10.972
24% of these treatment-naive tumors have

102
00:06:11.612 --> 00:06:15.572
downregulation of TAP2, which basically means that they have lower TAP2

103
00:06:15.592 --> 00:06:18.832
in the cancer cells than the non-cancer cells of the same specimen.

104
00:06:19.492 --> 00:06:23.352
But only 6% have downregulation of TAP1, and this was already

105
00:06:23.392 --> 00:06:27.292
interesting. We see this sort of asymmetric behavior where TAP2 is

106
00:06:27.592 --> 00:06:30.992
most commonly downregulated. But then another 18%

107
00:06:31.532 --> 00:06:34.192
had actually downregulation of both TAP1 and TAP2.

108
00:06:34.602 --> 00:06:38.372
And these are large numbers when you think that about half of treatment-naive lung

109
00:06:38.432 --> 00:06:41.472
cancers have an issue with TAP1, TAP2, or both.

110
00:06:43.032 --> 00:06:46.612
Now, what we see at the impact of this, again, these are baseline specimens

111
00:06:46.672 --> 00:06:50.512
from patients that went on to get treatment, we could see that those tumors with

112
00:06:50.612 --> 00:06:54.372
low TAP2, those patients did worse after treatment with

113
00:06:54.432 --> 00:06:55.092
immunotherapy.

114
00:06:55.892 --> 00:06:59.252
And this was quite consistent with a hazard ratio of 1.8, so

115
00:06:59.432 --> 00:07:03.132
80% more risk of dying when they were treated

116
00:07:03.652 --> 00:07:07.512
with low TAP2. So we know this is clinically meaningful,

117
00:07:07.572 --> 00:07:10.472
and it has consequences for the patient outcome.

118
00:07:11.052 --> 00:07:14.812
We did not see that with the downregulation of TAP1 or in patients that

119
00:07:15.092 --> 00:07:17.192
were treated with chemotherapy, so this seems to be

120
00:07:18.492 --> 00:07:19.652
immunotherapy specific.

121
00:07:21.512 --> 00:07:24.132
But then the main question came, okay, what's going on?

122
00:07:24.332 --> 00:07:27.752
Is this the obvious mechanism in which downregulation of

123
00:07:27.772 --> 00:07:31.452
TAP2 will be translating into fewer antigens? And we wanted to prove that.

124
00:07:31.932 --> 00:07:35.892
So the first thing we did was downregulating TAP1, TAP2, or both

125
00:07:35.902 --> 00:07:37.632
artificially in lung cancer cells.

126
00:07:37.672 --> 00:07:40.592
We tried KRAS and EGFR mutant lung cancer

127
00:07:40.632 --> 00:07:44.452
cells. We downregulated TAP1 or TAP2, and I

128
00:07:44.492 --> 00:07:46.472
will point you here to this figure.

129
00:07:46.832 --> 00:07:49.872
This is in the control condition or after treatment with cytokines.

130
00:07:50.712 --> 00:07:53.852
And if you see, the ones treated with interferon gamma TNF alpha,

131
00:07:54.972 --> 00:07:58.542
then we co-cultured these cancer cells with tumor

132
00:07:58.692 --> 00:08:02.632
antigen-specific T cells. So basically, these are CD8 T cells that express

133
00:08:02.672 --> 00:08:06.592
a TCR that recognize a cancer cell antigen that we know is

134
00:08:06.612 --> 00:08:09.112
expressed in the cancer cell, so again, tumor antigen-specific.

135
00:08:10.032 --> 00:08:13.651
We could see that when we downregulate TAP1, there was a significant

136
00:08:13.712 --> 00:08:17.492
reduction in T cell killing. When we removed TAP2, it

137
00:08:17.532 --> 00:08:21.362
was more pronounced, and when we removed TAP1 and TAP2, it was

138
00:08:21.392 --> 00:08:25.032
very similar to TAP2 alone. So this suggests that TAP2 has a dominant

139
00:08:25.072 --> 00:08:28.272
effect in protecting cancer cells from tumor

140
00:08:28.332 --> 00:08:29.512
antigen-specific killing.

141
00:08:31.712 --> 00:08:35.273
Then to show this more convincingly, we actually knock out

142
00:08:35.472 --> 00:08:39.332
TAP2, so this is different. The prior one was a small interference RNA, so knock

143
00:08:39.932 --> 00:08:42.893
down. This is knock out. We can see basically the same.

144
00:08:42.952 --> 00:08:46.932
You can see here again, when we remove TAP2 now totally, there

145
00:08:46.972 --> 00:08:49.532
was a significant reduction in the T cell killing.

146
00:08:50.492 --> 00:08:54.472
And then we knocked back in TAP2. We reintroduced TAP2,

147
00:08:54.492 --> 00:08:57.832
and we recovered the effect. So this clearly segregates with TAP2

148
00:08:58.412 --> 00:09:02.292
and points out its prominent effect in cancer cell protection.

149
00:09:03.552 --> 00:09:06.512
But then the question was, is this all mediated by antigen?

150
00:09:06.572 --> 00:09:10.292
And the reason why we brought up this question is because we saw

151
00:09:10.412 --> 00:09:14.092
things, as I showed you, that were not explained by reduced antigen.

152
00:09:14.692 --> 00:09:18.572
So to answer that question, we collaborated with a colleague, Etienne Caron at

153
00:09:18.612 --> 00:09:20.112
Yale, and we did immunopeptidomes.

154
00:09:20.172 --> 00:09:22.272
So basically, we take these lung cancer cells,

155
00:09:23.152 --> 00:09:26.172
with or without TAP2 expression, and then we do

156
00:09:26.252 --> 00:09:29.592
immunoprecipitation with a pan-HLA antibody.

157
00:09:29.892 --> 00:09:33.772
This is a very famous clone used by a lot of people, and then we pull it down

158
00:09:33.792 --> 00:09:37.012
and do mass spec. So now we can see changes in the entire

159
00:09:37.172 --> 00:09:40.972
repertoire of peptides that are loaded onto the HLA, in this case,

160
00:09:41.172 --> 00:09:42.112
HLA-A, B, and C.

161
00:09:43.712 --> 00:09:45.872
And what we could find was actually very interesting.

162
00:09:46.172 --> 00:09:49.092
Here we're seeing the wild type TAP2, and here the knockouts.

163
00:09:49.592 --> 00:09:52.852
And there was no change in the range of the size of the peptides.

164
00:09:52.892 --> 00:09:56.782
As expected, it peaked at nine amino acids with a range between about eight and

165
00:09:56.872 --> 00:10:00.862
12, very similar in the knockout. And then we saw about 10%

166
00:10:00.872 --> 00:10:04.172
to 15% reduction in the total amount of peptides loaded.

167
00:10:04.432 --> 00:10:08.232
And this was quite shocking, because what we expected was no antigens,

168
00:10:08.392 --> 00:10:10.512
because they were not pushed into the ER.

169
00:10:11.312 --> 00:10:14.272
And we actually saw a relatively mild reduction in the antigens.

170
00:10:15.192 --> 00:10:19.052
So this certainly did not explain the protection of the cancer

171
00:10:19.172 --> 00:10:22.891
cells by tumor antigen-specific killing assays.

172
00:10:24.032 --> 00:10:27.952
So then we said, okay, maybe there are other functions that are independent

173
00:10:27.992 --> 00:10:31.572
from the antigen. And this, I think, is the most interesting part because none of

174
00:10:31.632 --> 00:10:35.372
this has been looked at before. And I think I will try to

175
00:10:35.392 --> 00:10:38.892
convince you that these are actually arguably more important than the

176
00:10:38.932 --> 00:10:40.172
antigen-independent functions.

177
00:10:40.992 --> 00:10:44.412
So the first thing we did to look at this was knocking down

178
00:10:44.832 --> 00:10:48.652
TAP2 in lung cancer cells and do targeted transcriptomics.

179
00:10:49.372 --> 00:10:53.022
And one thing that came out that was quite impressive is that when we were

180
00:10:53.092 --> 00:10:57.072
just downregulating TAP2, we got downregulation of a number of relevant

181
00:10:57.132 --> 00:11:00.892
molecules, including TAP1, immunoproteasome components, chemokines, and

182
00:11:00.972 --> 00:11:04.022
cytokines. So just downregulation of TAP2 in the cancer cells

183
00:11:04.432 --> 00:11:07.412
produces and rewires the transcriptome of the cell.

184
00:11:08.272 --> 00:11:11.872
But then we found prominent upregulation of SOX1, which you can see here,

185
00:11:12.412 --> 00:11:16.292
that it's a very prominent and well-established inhibitor of interferon gamma

186
00:11:16.392 --> 00:11:20.312
signaling. SOX1 actually binds directly to JAK, which is downstream of the

187
00:11:20.392 --> 00:11:21.552
interferon gamma receptor.

188
00:11:22.432 --> 00:11:26.312
To validate this at the protein level, we again knocked down TAP2,

189
00:11:26.332 --> 00:11:29.892
and we could see increase in SOX1 by flow cytometry, so this is now

190
00:11:29.912 --> 00:11:32.652
protein. But this was actually bidirectional.

191
00:11:32.672 --> 00:11:36.652
We then transfected a flag TAP2,

192
00:11:36.852 --> 00:11:40.812
you can see here. When we overexpressed TAP2, SOX1 went down.

193
00:11:40.832 --> 00:11:44.452
So there is this bidirectional interaction between TAP2 and SOX1.

194
00:11:45.472 --> 00:11:49.072
Then we wanted to validate this in human tissue, so we took primary human tumors.

195
00:11:49.132 --> 00:11:53.032
We dissociated them, sorted the cancer cells, and we did

196
00:11:53.152 --> 00:11:55.172
RNA sequencing and ATAC sequencing.

197
00:11:55.212 --> 00:11:58.282
And what we found is exactly what I showed you in the cell lines.

198
00:11:58.332 --> 00:11:59.672
You can see here in the

199
00:12:00.872 --> 00:12:04.592
cancer relative to normal tissue, we saw downregulation of that TAP2 transcript,

200
00:12:04.632 --> 00:12:08.472
then upregulation of SOX1. So we have pretty good evidence that this

201
00:12:08.572 --> 00:12:12.532
mechanism is in place in human tumors, and it's not just a cell

202
00:12:12.572 --> 00:12:15.982
line artifact.Now,

203
00:12:16.342 --> 00:12:19.782
another interesting finding, and I think I told you that it was

204
00:12:19.842 --> 00:12:23.682
surprising that the tumors with low TAP2 had very few T cells that actually

205
00:12:23.742 --> 00:12:25.302
infiltrated the cancer cell nest.

206
00:12:25.862 --> 00:12:29.702
So we looked at the entire transcriptome of cells with and without TAP2

207
00:12:29.742 --> 00:12:33.462
knockout, and you can see that among transcripts that were

208
00:12:33.522 --> 00:12:37.482
upregulated was SOX1. So we confirmed this

209
00:12:37.542 --> 00:12:39.642
upregulation of this interferon gamma inhibitor.

210
00:12:40.262 --> 00:12:44.122
But then we found downregulation of a number of key chemokines that are critical

211
00:12:44.162 --> 00:12:47.632
for T-cell chemotraction, and we quantify a few of them.

212
00:12:47.702 --> 00:12:51.462
Below here you can see CXCL9 was non-significantly lower in the knockout,

213
00:12:51.542 --> 00:12:55.402
but CXCL10, CCL5, and CXCL11 were very

214
00:12:55.762 --> 00:12:59.382
low in the knockout. So what this supports is that the reduction of

215
00:12:59.462 --> 00:13:03.382
TAP2 can actually reduce the capacity of cancer cells to attract T

216
00:13:03.562 --> 00:13:06.982
cells, and that could explain that sort of immune exclusion

217
00:13:07.042 --> 00:13:07.602
phenotype.

218
00:13:08.422 --> 00:13:12.042
Interestingly, we did not see changes in the two interferon gamma receptors, so

219
00:13:12.082 --> 00:13:15.962
this is not just mediated by reduced expression of the

220
00:13:15.982 --> 00:13:19.881
receptors and most likely attributed to SOX1 upregulation.

221
00:13:22.142 --> 00:13:26.002
But then, because we saw this SOX1 effect, we decided to

222
00:13:26.022 --> 00:13:29.822
treat the cells with cytokines and see if the response to cytokines was

223
00:13:30.042 --> 00:13:32.102
different in cells with or without TAP2.

224
00:13:32.692 --> 00:13:36.422
And what you're seeing here are cells in the control knockdown or

225
00:13:36.482 --> 00:13:40.202
scrambled and in the TAP2 knockdown, we treat it with interferon

226
00:13:40.262 --> 00:13:41.762
gamma, and we look at the transcriptome.

227
00:13:42.422 --> 00:13:45.362
And what you can see that in the control condition, a number of interferon

228
00:13:45.402 --> 00:13:47.122
gamma-sensitive genes were upregulated.

229
00:13:47.182 --> 00:13:49.922
You can see IDO1, JAK, PD-L1, and so on.

230
00:13:50.922 --> 00:13:53.222
But in the knockdown, we could not see that.

231
00:13:53.382 --> 00:13:56.902
So clearly, the TAP2-deficient cells are less sensitive to

232
00:13:56.922 --> 00:14:00.812
interferon gamma, and a very similar response was seen when we treated with

233
00:14:00.862 --> 00:14:02.302
interferon gamma TNF alpha.

234
00:14:03.362 --> 00:14:06.922
Now, to validate this at the protein level, we took again lung cancer

235
00:14:07.042 --> 00:14:10.382
cells with or without a TAP2 knockout now, so not

236
00:14:11.302 --> 00:14:15.242
knockdown, but knockout. And you could see that upon treatment with interferon

237
00:14:15.282 --> 00:14:18.722
gamma, the amount of phosphorylated STAT1 was

238
00:14:18.822 --> 00:14:22.342
lower in the knockout. And then when we reintroduce

239
00:14:22.422 --> 00:14:26.262
TAP2, we recover the signaling of phospho-STAT1,

240
00:14:26.322 --> 00:14:28.302
which is known to be downstream of interferon gamma.

241
00:14:28.932 --> 00:14:31.562
And a very similar result was seen with IRF1.

242
00:14:32.002 --> 00:14:35.882
So collectively, this demonstrates that just downregulation of TAP2

243
00:14:36.302 --> 00:14:40.222
prevents the signaling of interferon gamma and TNF alpha, and

244
00:14:40.282 --> 00:14:44.191
makes cells resistant to interferon gamma and pro-inflammatory cytokines.

245
00:14:45.802 --> 00:14:47.422
We expanded this a little bit more.

246
00:14:47.482 --> 00:14:51.382
We did a phosphoprotein array with 37 signaling markers, and you can see that

247
00:14:51.402 --> 00:14:54.751
it's not only phosphorylated STAT1, there is downregulation of

248
00:14:54.762 --> 00:14:58.202
phosphorylated PLC gamma 1 and upregulation of phospho-STAT2.

249
00:14:58.242 --> 00:15:02.122
So basically, just manipulating TAP2 changes completely

250
00:15:02.562 --> 00:15:06.502
the inflammatory wiring of the cell, both transcriptionally but also in

251
00:15:06.542 --> 00:15:07.122
the signaling.

252
00:15:09.082 --> 00:15:12.942
Now, one fundamental question is how is TAP2 being downregulated

253
00:15:13.002 --> 00:15:16.882
in lung cancer cells? And generally, in cancer, we think about

254
00:15:16.982 --> 00:15:19.642
mutations, deletions, and genetic problems.

255
00:15:20.422 --> 00:15:24.342
So the first thing we did, we look at the TCGA lung cancer data set, which

256
00:15:24.382 --> 00:15:28.202
is about 875 lung adenocarcinomas and squamous

257
00:15:28.222 --> 00:15:32.142
carcinomas. And we look at deleterious mutations in TAP2 gene,

258
00:15:32.382 --> 00:15:33.422
basically meaning

259
00:15:34.422 --> 00:15:38.322
nonsense mutations or biallelic losses and things that would really

260
00:15:38.422 --> 00:15:40.342
compromise the structure of the gene.

261
00:15:40.962 --> 00:15:44.932
And we could find only about 1% of cases that had deleterious

262
00:15:45.002 --> 00:15:48.882
TAP2 mutations. So clearly, downregulation of TAP2

263
00:15:48.922 --> 00:15:52.822
is not a consequence of a genetic alteration in the vast majority of cases.

264
00:15:53.842 --> 00:15:56.822
So we hypothesized that this could have been an epigenetic effect.

265
00:15:57.122 --> 00:16:00.922
So we ran primary tumors using ATAC-seq, and we

266
00:16:00.962 --> 00:16:04.882
compared the lung cancer with adjacent non-tumor tissue, which is

267
00:16:05.242 --> 00:16:09.142
indicated as NAT. And what we could see, and is shown here, is that in

268
00:16:09.162 --> 00:16:13.122
the cancer, the promoter region of TAP2, which is three kilobases above

269
00:16:13.202 --> 00:16:17.082
and below the ATG, the start codon, was significantly

270
00:16:17.142 --> 00:16:20.812
reduced. So basically, the accessibility of the chromatin is shut down,

271
00:16:21.262 --> 00:16:24.002
and TAP2 is likely being less transcribed.

272
00:16:24.542 --> 00:16:28.202
And we'll identify a couple of motifs of transcription factors that are

273
00:16:28.242 --> 00:16:32.082
binding that region that could actually explain why TAP2 is being

274
00:16:32.161 --> 00:16:34.551
silenced epigenetically in human tumors.

275
00:16:36.661 --> 00:16:39.802
Then the question was how is this happening? Who is mediating this?

276
00:16:40.082 --> 00:16:43.862
And after a number of experiments, we identified that tumors, human

277
00:16:43.942 --> 00:16:47.762
tumors with low TAP2, generally had more interleukin-4

278
00:16:47.822 --> 00:16:51.762
on bulk transcriptome analysis. So we hypothesized that interleukin-4 could

279
00:16:51.782 --> 00:16:55.582
do this. So we treat both KRAS and EGFR

280
00:16:55.622 --> 00:16:59.502
mutant lung cancer cells with recombinant human IL4, and we could

281
00:16:59.562 --> 00:17:03.492
actually rapidly reduce TAP2. You can see that within 12 hours,

282
00:17:03.562 --> 00:17:07.562
we could see significant reduction in the levels of TAP2 protein, which

283
00:17:07.603 --> 00:17:11.272
demonstrates that IL4 is sufficient to downregulate TAP2 in cancer cells.

284
00:17:12.042 --> 00:17:15.962
Now, not surprisingly, the effect of IL4 was

285
00:17:16.083 --> 00:17:19.542
epigenetically. You can see here that we could reduce the chromatin

286
00:17:19.583 --> 00:17:23.402
accessibility in the TAP2 promoter, just adding IL4, and it was

287
00:17:23.462 --> 00:17:27.242
only partially restored when we co-treated with interferon gamma and TNF alpha.

288
00:17:27.742 --> 00:17:31.722
And this is important because there has been this notion in the field that antigen

289
00:17:31.742 --> 00:17:35.682
presentation is not a big problem because it can be corrected with interferon gamma

290
00:17:35.742 --> 00:17:38.602
or some inflammatory stimuli. But we actually don't see that.

291
00:17:39.382 --> 00:17:43.182
You can see, for example, here, when we treat with cells with IL4, we see a

292
00:17:43.222 --> 00:17:46.962
reduction in TAP2. We add cytokines, and we don't

293
00:17:47.002 --> 00:17:49.282
restore the level to a normal situation.

294
00:17:49.362 --> 00:17:50.062
So basically,

295
00:17:51.442 --> 00:17:55.182
just adding inflammation or inflammatory cytokines doesn't restore the

296
00:17:55.202 --> 00:17:55.602
problem.

297
00:17:56.482 --> 00:18:00.212
Not surprisingly, you can see here that SOX1 was upregulated by

298
00:18:00.302 --> 00:18:03.522
IL4, which is consistent with the data we have seen in tumors and

299
00:18:03.582 --> 00:18:07.206
cells.To

300
00:18:07.246 --> 00:18:10.386
confirm that, we actually went back and looked at the human tumors.

301
00:18:10.746 --> 00:18:14.406
We look at the IL4 RNA because the cytokine can be

302
00:18:14.446 --> 00:18:17.666
secreted and that's problematic for detection, but the RNA is not.

303
00:18:18.306 --> 00:18:22.106
So we actually look at tumors, and this is an example of a cancer.

304
00:18:22.166 --> 00:18:24.086
You can see the cancer cells are in green.

305
00:18:24.606 --> 00:18:28.586
They lack TAP2 expression, but TAP2 is fine in the non-cancer cells.

306
00:18:29.166 --> 00:18:32.996
And you can see a lot of IL4 RNA, mostly colocalizing with

307
00:18:33.046 --> 00:18:37.026
CD11b. So these are most likely myeloid-derived suppressor

308
00:18:37.046 --> 00:18:39.286
cells that are interspersed the cancer cells.

309
00:18:39.686 --> 00:18:43.486
They're producing IL4 locally, and that could mediate the

310
00:18:44.186 --> 00:18:47.346
suppression in TAP2 that I just showed you using in vitro experiments.

311
00:18:49.386 --> 00:18:51.646
Now, the big question is can we do something about it?

312
00:18:52.206 --> 00:18:53.996
And this is important, because

313
00:18:55.086 --> 00:18:59.046
the fact that the genes are fine and that this is epigenetic opens

314
00:18:59.066 --> 00:19:02.346
the possibility to actually restore expression of TAP2.

315
00:19:03.186 --> 00:19:06.926
So to answer that question, the first idea was to block IL4

316
00:19:06.976 --> 00:19:10.616
signaling, and fortunately, interleukin-4 has only one receptor, so we can

317
00:19:10.646 --> 00:19:14.326
effectively target that receptor using antibodies.

318
00:19:14.366 --> 00:19:18.106
So we took primary human tumors, we desegregated them into single-cell

319
00:19:18.166 --> 00:19:21.926
suspensions, and then we separated cancer cells and T cells in an

320
00:19:21.966 --> 00:19:25.426
autologous fashion. So these are fully matched by all HLAs

321
00:19:26.106 --> 00:19:27.246
and they're fully human.

322
00:19:28.186 --> 00:19:31.846
And then we co-cultured them with or without treatment with an IL4

323
00:19:31.886 --> 00:19:35.726
blocking antibody, plus minus pembrolizumab, which is an anti-PD-1.

324
00:19:36.666 --> 00:19:40.586
And then we measure CD8 T cell activation using CD25, and then we

325
00:19:40.626 --> 00:19:44.506
look at autologous T cell killing using annexin V expression

326
00:19:44.546 --> 00:19:46.786
of EpCAM positive malignant cells.

327
00:19:47.556 --> 00:19:51.386
And what you can see is that when we added both the blocker of IL4

328
00:19:51.426 --> 00:19:55.246
and pembrolizumab, we could significantly increase the activation of CD8

329
00:19:55.286 --> 00:19:55.736
T cells.

330
00:19:56.946 --> 00:20:00.826
And then we could also enhance the cancer cell killing ability, which

331
00:20:00.866 --> 00:20:04.846
demonstrates that just blocking the IL4 receptor can enhance the

332
00:20:04.886 --> 00:20:06.356
activity of checkpoint blockade.

333
00:20:07.026 --> 00:20:10.446
Now, in parallel, when we were working on this, there was a paper by Miriam Merad's

334
00:20:10.486 --> 00:20:13.746
group showing in a clinical trial that blocking the IL4 receptor

335
00:20:14.406 --> 00:20:15.446
using a commercial

336
00:20:16.306 --> 00:20:20.026
drug that it's currently approved for asthma was actually beneficial for patients

337
00:20:20.066 --> 00:20:22.686
with lung cancer refractory to checkpoint blockade.

338
00:20:22.706 --> 00:20:26.546
So we believe that this is actually already translated clinically

339
00:20:26.606 --> 00:20:27.465
from another group.

340
00:20:30.226 --> 00:20:32.486
But then the question was, can we do something else?

341
00:20:32.646 --> 00:20:36.226
And I just showed you that this is an epigenetic mechanism, so we

342
00:20:36.266 --> 00:20:40.026
thought that there could be ways that we could use repurposed

343
00:20:40.146 --> 00:20:44.046
drugs, mostly epigenetic modulators, to re-express TAP2 in the

344
00:20:44.086 --> 00:20:46.806
cancer cells and bypass the IL4 effect.

345
00:20:47.786 --> 00:20:51.666
So to answer that question, we did a drug screen where we set up

346
00:20:51.706 --> 00:20:54.846
an assay to look at cancer cells, lung cancer cells.

347
00:20:54.866 --> 00:20:58.766
We treated them with about 3,000 compounds, many of which are FDA

348
00:20:58.775 --> 00:21:00.746
approved and some epigenetic modulators.

349
00:21:01.326 --> 00:21:04.506
And then we look for upregulation of TAP2 and

350
00:21:04.586 --> 00:21:08.396
upregulation of PD-L1. And what we were focusing on are

351
00:21:08.406 --> 00:21:11.836
drugs that could upregulate TAP2 without upregulating PD-L1.

352
00:21:11.866 --> 00:21:15.806
And this is relevant because both PD-L1 and TAP2 are sensitive to interferon gamma,

353
00:21:15.886 --> 00:21:17.606
so we didn't want to upregulate both.

354
00:21:18.266 --> 00:21:22.226
And as you can see here in the red dots, we found a number of compounds

355
00:21:22.266 --> 00:21:25.366
that could upregulate TAP2 without modifying PD-L1.

356
00:21:25.686 --> 00:21:29.546
So basically, we were trying to harness the pro-inflammatory effect without the

357
00:21:29.555 --> 00:21:30.646
immunosuppressive effect.

358
00:21:33.526 --> 00:21:37.506
A summary of the compounds that we identify is shown here on the bottom left,

359
00:21:37.606 --> 00:21:41.586
and surprisingly, we found agents that are already used in anti-cancer

360
00:21:41.686 --> 00:21:45.526
treatment in lung cancer. You can see dasatinib is a tyrosine kinase inhibitors

361
00:21:45.546 --> 00:21:49.346
approved for lung cancer. But then a number of taxanes, actually three

362
00:21:49.366 --> 00:21:50.706
taxanes, docetaxel,

363
00:21:51.526 --> 00:21:53.745
and a few others came out in the screen.

364
00:21:53.766 --> 00:21:57.546
Now, taxanes are used usually in the second line and above in lung cancer

365
00:21:57.646 --> 00:22:00.806
patients, and they're known to be inflammatory, but nobody knows why.

366
00:22:01.166 --> 00:22:04.946
Because they're supposed to do microtubule disaggregation.

367
00:22:05.646 --> 00:22:09.566
So we believe there's a big component here that could explain why taxanes

368
00:22:09.606 --> 00:22:13.436
are so inflammatory. But then interestingly, you can see here we found a

369
00:22:13.486 --> 00:22:17.326
number of HDAC inhibitors. These are three, two of

370
00:22:17.366 --> 00:22:21.126
which are already approved. SAHA is vorinostat, is approved for heme

371
00:22:21.166 --> 00:22:25.046
malignancies. And you can see that there were two pan-HDAC

372
00:22:25.086 --> 00:22:27.186
inhibitors and one HDAC6 inhibitor.

373
00:22:27.266 --> 00:22:30.546
So that we then treated the cells with some of these compounds.

374
00:22:30.586 --> 00:22:32.486
This is an example of vorinostat or SAHA.

375
00:22:33.086 --> 00:22:36.806
You can see that we could increase TAP2 expression, increase antigens in the

376
00:22:36.826 --> 00:22:39.746
surface, and increase the tumor antigen-specific killing.

377
00:22:39.806 --> 00:22:43.086
So just adding, in this case, SAHA, could restore

378
00:22:43.446 --> 00:22:46.686
the functionality and the tumor antigen-specific killing.

379
00:22:46.726 --> 00:22:50.646
So we believe there are good avenues here to use repurposed drugs to

380
00:22:50.686 --> 00:22:54.246
be able to treat patients that have defective TAP2

381
00:22:54.286 --> 00:22:54.826
expression.

382
00:22:56.906 --> 00:23:00.746
So in summary from this part, what I hope I convince you

383
00:23:00.846 --> 00:23:04.766
of is that there is this non-antigen dependent effect

384
00:23:04.946 --> 00:23:08.926
of TAP2 downregulation. I actually kind of minimized the

385
00:23:09.026 --> 00:23:12.026
antigen part, which we do see about 20% reduction in the antigens.

386
00:23:12.086 --> 00:23:15.326
But we found this interesting intercellular axis where

387
00:23:15.406 --> 00:23:19.346
myeloid-derived suppressor cells that are CD11b positive within

388
00:23:19.386 --> 00:23:23.186
the cancer produce IL4 that signals via IL4

389
00:23:23.196 --> 00:23:25.726
receptor and produces at least two effects.

390
00:23:25.786 --> 00:23:29.366
One, which is silencing epigenetically TAP2, which

391
00:23:29.426 --> 00:23:33.226
increases SOX1 and shuts down interferon gamma signaling, and then

392
00:23:33.246 --> 00:23:37.026
also there is a reduction in chemokines and pro-inflammatory signals that makes

393
00:23:37.086 --> 00:23:39.066
these tumors more immune-evasive.

394
00:23:39.526 --> 00:23:43.186
And I think the most important thing is that this can be targeted.

395
00:23:44.586 --> 00:23:48.356
Now, one other question we ask, and this is unpublished, is

396
00:23:48.786 --> 00:23:51.946
does this mechanism project during cancer progression?

397
00:23:52.666 --> 00:23:56.566
So to answer that question, we collected primary human lung cancers in

398
00:23:56.606 --> 00:24:00.586
a cohort of lung cancer brain metastases, and we just wanted to compare the

399
00:24:00.626 --> 00:24:04.446
levels, in this case, of beta-2 microglobulin and phosphorylated

400
00:24:04.546 --> 00:24:08.386
STAT1 or IRF1. Examples of the staining is shown

401
00:24:08.446 --> 00:24:11.636
here. And I won't go into too much detail because of

402
00:24:11.686 --> 00:24:15.499
time.We measured two independent cohorts, and what was really

403
00:24:15.550 --> 00:24:19.510
fascinating is that in both cohorts, we could see that lung cancer brain

404
00:24:19.530 --> 00:24:23.480
metastases, which are shown as LBM, consistently had lower

405
00:24:23.570 --> 00:24:25.750
beta-2 microglobulin than the primary tumors.

406
00:24:26.670 --> 00:24:30.150
But this was not true in the extracranial metastases.

407
00:24:30.210 --> 00:24:33.650
So only the brain metastases had downregulation of beta-2m,

408
00:24:34.490 --> 00:24:37.610
while phosphorylated STAT1 and IRF1 were comparable.

409
00:24:37.670 --> 00:24:41.510
So this basically is a different mechanism, where now interferon gamma

410
00:24:41.630 --> 00:24:45.570
signaling is preserved, but the brain mets had even lower antigen

411
00:24:45.590 --> 00:24:47.390
presentation proteins than the primaries.

412
00:24:47.830 --> 00:24:50.010
And this was quite consistent in the second cohort.

413
00:24:50.470 --> 00:24:54.090
You can see here again the lung brain metastasis, lower beta-2m, no

414
00:24:54.210 --> 00:24:57.770
difference with the extracranial metastasis, and comparable levels of interferon

415
00:24:57.810 --> 00:25:01.110
gamma signaling. So now we're trying to understand if this is a

416
00:25:01.250 --> 00:25:05.190
consequence of the brain metastases, or it could actually be the cause of

417
00:25:05.210 --> 00:25:08.430
brain metastases and try to intervene in that process.

418
00:25:08.470 --> 00:25:12.050
And we have a manuscript under revision where we actually are looking at the

419
00:25:12.130 --> 00:25:13.930
mechanisms, but I will not go into that.

420
00:25:14.810 --> 00:25:18.730
Now when we compared the subset of patients that had paired samples, so these

421
00:25:18.790 --> 00:25:21.890
are primary and brain metastases from the same patient

422
00:25:21.990 --> 00:25:25.730
longitudinally, we can see again a significant downregulation of

423
00:25:25.890 --> 00:25:29.190
beta-2m in the cancer cells, but also in the stromal cells.

424
00:25:29.250 --> 00:25:33.010
And this is really interesting because it seems to be a field effect, like both the

425
00:25:33.050 --> 00:25:36.660
cancer cells and the neighboring non-cancer cells have lower antigen

426
00:25:36.670 --> 00:25:40.590
presentation. No significant difference in interferon gamma signaling,

427
00:25:40.970 --> 00:25:43.710
supporting that this is an independent mechanism.

428
00:25:45.950 --> 00:25:49.870
We also look at TAP1 and TAP2, and a long story short, we do not

429
00:25:49.970 --> 00:25:53.370
see differences in TAP1 between primary lung, brain, and

430
00:25:53.510 --> 00:25:57.010
extracranial metastases. And we see a slight reduction of

431
00:25:57.050 --> 00:26:00.510
TAP2, which is the boundary of significance, it's actually

432
00:26:00.550 --> 00:26:03.230
significant in the stromal cells, but not in the cancer cells.

433
00:26:03.750 --> 00:26:07.490
But now we don't see a difference between the lung brain metastases and the

434
00:26:07.570 --> 00:26:11.190
extracranial. So it seems like metastatic cells in the

435
00:26:11.230 --> 00:26:14.770
brain down-regulate beta-2 microglobulin, but not in

436
00:26:14.850 --> 00:26:18.530
the extracranial metastases. But now all the metastases

437
00:26:18.570 --> 00:26:21.230
down-regulate TAP2. So this is really

438
00:26:22.129 --> 00:26:25.970
getting very granular, and I think we will need to study more to try to

439
00:26:26.050 --> 00:26:28.250
perturb those systems.

440
00:26:29.550 --> 00:26:32.090
Now, what about other tumor types? Again, this is also unpublished.

441
00:26:32.130 --> 00:26:35.830
We look at this in colorectal cancer, and this is data you can see here.

442
00:26:35.890 --> 00:26:39.830
This is what we call an uneventful or normal tumor, if you

443
00:26:39.850 --> 00:26:42.870
want, which TAP1 and TAP2 are expressed everywhere,

444
00:26:43.650 --> 00:26:47.590
unaltered TAP1 and TAP2. You can see the cancer cells express it, the

445
00:26:47.690 --> 00:26:51.450
non-cancer cells, and this is a case in colorectal cancer where the cancer

446
00:26:51.490 --> 00:26:55.350
cells lost TAP1 and TAP2. You can see that normal cells are fine,

447
00:26:55.430 --> 00:26:57.250
but the cancer cells don't express it.

448
00:26:57.910 --> 00:27:01.790
Now when we look at this again at scale, we look at a little over 400 tumors.

449
00:27:01.850 --> 00:27:04.930
We see that 16% of colorectal cancers lose TAP2,

450
00:27:05.450 --> 00:27:09.449
10% TAP1, and 30% lose both. So it's similar to lung, but

451
00:27:09.510 --> 00:27:13.070
not the same. And this adds another layer of complexity, which is that

452
00:27:13.410 --> 00:27:15.850
different tumor types may have different

453
00:27:16.670 --> 00:27:20.450
dominant mechanisms of immunivation, and I think we should think carefully

454
00:27:20.530 --> 00:27:22.590
about their significance in that context.

455
00:27:23.690 --> 00:27:24.870
Certainly not only lung.

456
00:27:26.290 --> 00:27:29.870
So in conclusion from the first part, I hope I convinced you that immunivation in

457
00:27:29.970 --> 00:27:33.250
lung cancer involves complex TME interactions between cancer and

458
00:27:33.330 --> 00:27:37.170
non-malignant cells. Here we found this axis between myeloid cells, cancer

459
00:27:37.250 --> 00:27:38.150
cells, and T cells.

460
00:27:39.250 --> 00:27:42.950
TAP2 loss or downregulation is frequent in lung cancer, mediates

461
00:27:42.990 --> 00:27:46.810
immunivation resistance to immunotherapy, and there is a possible role in

462
00:27:46.830 --> 00:27:50.570
colorectal cancer and brain metastases, both of which could also be harnessed

463
00:27:50.590 --> 00:27:51.220
therapeutically.

464
00:27:52.490 --> 00:27:56.310
Three, that the mechanisms of immunivation in lung cancer associated with TAP2

465
00:27:56.330 --> 00:28:00.150
loss include antigen-independent effects, and I believe that these actually

466
00:28:00.170 --> 00:28:04.110
are more relevant than the antigen-dependent effects, which I think that we

467
00:28:04.170 --> 00:28:05.750
generally associate with this biology.

468
00:28:06.590 --> 00:28:10.430
And finally, the TAP2 downregulation in lung cancer is epigenetically in

469
00:28:10.510 --> 00:28:10.850
nature,

470
00:28:11.670 --> 00:28:14.550
and the most important thing, that it's reversible, so there's something we can do

471
00:28:14.630 --> 00:28:18.450
about it, either blocking IL-4 signaling or using epigenetic

472
00:28:18.530 --> 00:28:22.130
modulators. And now we're planning a clinical trial where we're selecting patients

473
00:28:22.210 --> 00:28:25.950
based on low TAP2, and we're planning interventions that include

474
00:28:26.010 --> 00:28:29.940
taxanes and epigenetic modulators to validate this further

475
00:28:29.970 --> 00:28:30.989
and try to exploit it.

476
00:28:33.669 --> 00:28:36.950
So now in the second part of the lecture, I'll talk about another really

477
00:28:37.010 --> 00:28:40.870
interesting tumor immune cell interaction, which is something that has been known

478
00:28:40.910 --> 00:28:44.510
in the field as immune exclusion. And what I mean by that is

479
00:28:45.050 --> 00:28:48.890
shown here in the slide, where you can see that the majority of T cells and B cells

480
00:28:49.410 --> 00:28:53.100
are in the stroma, yet they don't enter very well the

481
00:28:53.100 --> 00:28:56.370
cancer cell nest. Again, it's shown in green cytokeratin.

482
00:28:56.730 --> 00:29:00.420
You can see that most of the CD8s, which are red, are in the stroma, and

483
00:29:00.470 --> 00:29:02.830
very few are actually able to enter.

484
00:29:03.130 --> 00:29:06.170
And this is on a quantitative level, it's actually pretty prominent.

485
00:29:06.210 --> 00:29:10.010
You can see that we find five times more CD4s and CD8 in the

486
00:29:10.110 --> 00:29:12.690
stroma than in the cancer cell nest.

487
00:29:12.730 --> 00:29:16.450
And this is problematic because I just showed you that to recognize the

488
00:29:16.510 --> 00:29:18.870
cancer cell, the T cells need to enter in contact.

489
00:29:18.910 --> 00:29:22.850
They need to see the TCR antigen interaction.

490
00:29:22.910 --> 00:29:24.930
So to do that, they need to be in touch.

491
00:29:25.470 --> 00:29:29.170
But then after the recognition, to kill, they need to exert their

492
00:29:29.230 --> 00:29:32.930
mechanisms of cytotoxicity, which are perforin granzyme system,

493
00:29:33.290 --> 00:29:37.130
cytokines such as interferon or TNF alpha, or death receptors such

494
00:29:37.170 --> 00:29:40.790
as Fas. All of these mechanisms require proximity.

495
00:29:40.850 --> 00:29:44.750
So the main question is, if we have these lymphocytes in the stroma, how are

496
00:29:44.790 --> 00:29:48.630
they recognizing TCR antigens, and how are they executing the

497
00:29:48.650 --> 00:29:51.150
killing? This really doesn't make any sense.

498
00:29:52.090 --> 00:29:55.480
So the problem, I think, in the field is that we pathologists, and

499
00:29:55.730 --> 00:29:57.470
generally we kind of accepted that.

500
00:29:57.590 --> 00:30:00.710
I don't think it's news for everyone here that, oh, yeah, the majority of immune

501
00:30:00.730 --> 00:30:04.650
cells are in the stroma. But we haven't done anything about it, and it's

502
00:30:04.750 --> 00:30:06.230
actually been relatively difficult.

503
00:30:06.810 --> 00:30:08.950
So many years ago, we started thinking about it,

504
00:30:09.850 --> 00:30:13.642
and we elaborated a little bit more on this idea that has been...

505
00:30:13.702 --> 00:30:16.682
pointed before and was recently reviewed by us.

506
00:30:16.882 --> 00:30:20.782
And Miguel, who is a very talented postdoc who is sitting in the audience, spent

507
00:30:20.822 --> 00:30:23.522
time here with other colleagues writing this.

508
00:30:24.222 --> 00:30:26.702
We actually look at the evidence of these phenotypes.

509
00:30:26.722 --> 00:30:27.582
And the traditional

510
00:30:28.502 --> 00:30:32.402
view is that there are tumors that are infiltrated, so they have CD8 T

511
00:30:32.422 --> 00:30:35.942
cells in the cancer cell nest. There are excluded

512
00:30:35.982 --> 00:30:39.942
tumors in which the CD8s are in the boundary or the periphery,

513
00:30:40.022 --> 00:30:43.962
but they cannot enter, and then immune desert tumors, which basically have no

514
00:30:44.002 --> 00:30:44.382
T cells.

515
00:30:45.462 --> 00:30:47.562
And these are examples of those patterns.

516
00:30:47.582 --> 00:30:48.282
You can see here

517
00:30:49.122 --> 00:30:51.722
one, two, and three representing this cartoon.

518
00:30:52.402 --> 00:30:55.922
Now, what is the problem is that when we actually look at real human tumors, and

519
00:30:55.962 --> 00:30:59.542
you're seeing one here on the right, we can find the three patterns in the same

520
00:30:59.642 --> 00:31:03.482
tumor. And this is very common. So when we do eyeballing basically,

521
00:31:03.502 --> 00:31:06.502
or estimation, we're very likely to not know what to do.

522
00:31:06.882 --> 00:31:10.262
Because if we look at this region, we find one pattern, if we look at this region,

523
00:31:10.322 --> 00:31:11.662
we find another pattern, and so on.

524
00:31:12.322 --> 00:31:16.102
So we really didn't have the right tools to ask questions

525
00:31:16.142 --> 00:31:17.222
about immune exclusion.

526
00:31:19.342 --> 00:31:23.122
So to address that question, again, Miguel spent some time looking at this, and we

527
00:31:23.182 --> 00:31:26.822
basically quantified the cells in the cancer cell nest and in the

528
00:31:26.882 --> 00:31:30.842
stroma. And with a very simple ratio of density of the

529
00:31:30.882 --> 00:31:34.542
cells in the tumor, in the stroma associated with k-means clustering, we

530
00:31:34.602 --> 00:31:38.382
actually found patterns that are consistent, measurable, and reproducible,

531
00:31:38.802 --> 00:31:42.272
where we can see a subset of tumors where the majority of areas are

532
00:31:42.282 --> 00:31:44.682
excluded, which are shown here as zero ratio.

533
00:31:45.322 --> 00:31:46.042
So most of the

534
00:31:46.942 --> 00:31:48.922
lymphocytes are within the cancer cell nest.

535
00:31:49.462 --> 00:31:53.222
Then we found another group where the majority of lymphocytes were in areas of the

536
00:31:53.302 --> 00:31:56.862
tumor that were infiltrated, so they were in the cancer cell nest.

537
00:31:57.562 --> 00:32:01.442
And then we found the tumors that had both exclusion, shown here again

538
00:32:01.482 --> 00:32:04.162
as zero, and infiltration, shown here.

539
00:32:04.182 --> 00:32:07.442
But these three patterns were consistent and were selected in an

540
00:32:07.502 --> 00:32:10.972
unsupervised fashion. So it was the algorithm and not our cells

541
00:32:11.002 --> 00:32:14.442
deciding what is what. And then we look at the

542
00:32:15.122 --> 00:32:18.502
survival of those tumors measured at baseline after

543
00:32:18.522 --> 00:32:19.202
immunotherapy.

544
00:32:20.022 --> 00:32:23.782
And what you can see that altogether we found that about 20% of tumors have this

545
00:32:23.821 --> 00:32:25.622
immune excluded-like phenotype.

546
00:32:25.682 --> 00:32:29.062
So basically again, the majority of fields of view have exclusion.

547
00:32:29.662 --> 00:32:33.432
About 20% were what we called infiltrated-like or dominated by

548
00:32:33.542 --> 00:32:37.182
cancer cell infiltration, and then about 60% were all over the place.

549
00:32:38.062 --> 00:32:41.752
But the interesting thing is that when we look at the survival after immunotherapy,

550
00:32:41.982 --> 00:32:45.582
only the ones showing this immune excluded-like phenotype did actually worse.

551
00:32:45.962 --> 00:32:49.582
And this is collapsed here on the right where we actually think this

552
00:32:49.722 --> 00:32:53.522
meaningful. So basically those tumors with more exclusion do worse after

553
00:32:53.542 --> 00:32:55.862
immunotherapy, supporting that this is a relevant

554
00:32:56.742 --> 00:32:57.822
spatial orientation.

555
00:33:00.222 --> 00:33:04.082
But then the question, and so far, I think the dominating paradigm has

556
00:33:04.122 --> 00:33:07.262
been that exclusion is a passive phenomenon.

557
00:33:07.302 --> 00:33:11.002
What I mean by that is that we have always thought that excluded tumors

558
00:33:11.082 --> 00:33:14.082
lack something. They lack antigen, they lack dendritic cells,

559
00:33:15.022 --> 00:33:15.932
something is missing.

560
00:33:16.902 --> 00:33:20.492
But we challenge that hypothesis with the idea that maybe this is an active

561
00:33:20.562 --> 00:33:24.242
phenomenon. Maybe cancer cells can produce something that will

562
00:33:24.382 --> 00:33:28.142
slow down or keep T cells away. And this is work done in

563
00:33:28.162 --> 00:33:31.802
collaboration with Liping Chen lab, and Jason Zhang spent a number of

564
00:33:32.362 --> 00:33:33.122
years actually

565
00:33:34.062 --> 00:33:37.242
generating this migration assay where he took a

566
00:33:37.322 --> 00:33:41.122
modified Boyden chamber and add CXCL11 on

567
00:33:41.182 --> 00:33:44.442
one side to induce migration and transfected a number of soluble

568
00:33:44.622 --> 00:33:48.322
factors into cancer cells to find molecules that

569
00:33:48.382 --> 00:33:52.202
which could be expressed in the cancer cell and would slow down T cell

570
00:33:52.222 --> 00:33:52.762
migration.

571
00:33:53.862 --> 00:33:57.062
In a long story short, you can see here one such molecule called

572
00:33:57.082 --> 00:34:00.812
PLA2G10. This is a group 10 phospholipase that, as shown

573
00:34:00.882 --> 00:34:04.222
here, upon treatment, the lymphocytes slowed down.

574
00:34:04.402 --> 00:34:08.382
There was fewer migration induced by CXCL11, CXCL19,

575
00:34:08.542 --> 00:34:12.322
and a number of other molecules, and blockade of that PLA2G10

576
00:34:12.382 --> 00:34:16.263
actually reduce or restore the migration of the lymphocyte.

577
00:34:16.642 --> 00:34:20.602
So this is the concept of what we're now calling T cell excluders, which are

578
00:34:20.622 --> 00:34:24.283
molecules that the cancer cell can produce that will slow down or

579
00:34:24.502 --> 00:34:28.082
stop T cells and could explain this immune exclusion

580
00:34:28.142 --> 00:34:28.682
phenotype.

581
00:34:30.263 --> 00:34:34.022
Now, to prove this experimentally, we generated a mouse model where we

582
00:34:34.082 --> 00:34:37.922
overexpress this PLA2G10. This is KPC pancreatic, and we also

583
00:34:37.942 --> 00:34:41.422
did MC38. And you can see that overexpression of

584
00:34:41.462 --> 00:34:43.662
PLA2G10 enhanced the cancer

585
00:34:44.803 --> 00:34:45.172
growth,

586
00:34:46.022 --> 00:34:49.743
and also reduced the number of T cells, and it was synergistic with

587
00:34:49.822 --> 00:34:53.622
anti-PD-1. This is 1C11, is an antibody that blocks the catalytic domain of

588
00:34:53.692 --> 00:34:57.482
PLA2G10. So there was a good rationale in vivo that

589
00:34:57.622 --> 00:35:01.442
blocking PLA2G10 could enhance tumor rejection and T

590
00:35:01.582 --> 00:35:02.342
cell infiltration.

591
00:35:04.102 --> 00:35:07.492
But then we also want to confirm that in human tumors, and this is

592
00:35:07.522 --> 00:35:11.422
TCGA data, we could see upregulation of this PLA2G10 in lung cancer

593
00:35:11.522 --> 00:35:15.242
relative to normal lung. And then we generate an assay, and we could actually

594
00:35:15.302 --> 00:35:18.442
find lung cancer cells shown here in green that express

595
00:35:18.482 --> 00:35:22.172
PLA2G10. And this is really interesting because I just told you that

596
00:35:22.182 --> 00:35:24.262
PLA2G10 is a secreted phospholipase.

597
00:35:24.612 --> 00:35:28.182
So somehow the cancer cells are producing or retaining

598
00:35:28.222 --> 00:35:31.742
PLA2G10 locally to mediate the

599
00:35:32.022 --> 00:35:35.782
effect on T cells. And as shown here, tumors with very

600
00:35:35.822 --> 00:35:39.442
high PLA2G10 in the cancer cells generally had fewer

601
00:35:39.742 --> 00:35:41.922
infiltration, particularly of CD8 T cells.

602
00:35:41.942 --> 00:35:45.412
So we have pretty good evidence that this idea of T cell

603
00:35:45.462 --> 00:35:49.402
exclusion, active T cell exclusion, works both experimentally but

604
00:35:49.562 --> 00:35:50.522
in human tumors too.

605
00:35:52.822 --> 00:35:56.502
So then finally, we wanted to look at this from another side.

606
00:35:57.042 --> 00:36:01.022
And we basically thought that we may be able to discover more of these T cell

607
00:36:01.122 --> 00:36:02.902
excluders by now looking at tissue.

608
00:36:03.482 --> 00:36:07.142
So what we did here, we collected 250 primary lung cancers.

609
00:36:07.582 --> 00:36:11.502
We analyzed them with a panel, as I just showed you before, and then we

610
00:36:11.582 --> 00:36:14.602
used the formula that we created to identify T cell

611
00:36:14.642 --> 00:36:18.602
exclusion.We took this cohort of 250 tumors, and we went

612
00:36:18.662 --> 00:36:22.482
to the top 20% more excluded and 20% more

613
00:36:22.542 --> 00:36:26.162
infiltrated. And we analyzed them, as shown here, using our

614
00:36:26.202 --> 00:36:28.762
algorithm, and this is an example of an excluded tumor.

615
00:36:28.822 --> 00:36:32.662
You can see that the immune cells are in the stroma. This is important.

616
00:36:32.682 --> 00:36:35.242
There are immune cells, they're just in the wrong place.

617
00:36:35.922 --> 00:36:38.962
And then this is an immune-infiltrated tumor, where you can see that the majority

618
00:36:39.022 --> 00:36:41.522
of cells can actually enter the cancer cell nest.

619
00:36:41.842 --> 00:36:43.462
So this is just an example of what we did.

620
00:36:44.742 --> 00:36:48.322
But then we analyzed them using spatial transcriptomics to try to focus on

621
00:36:48.381 --> 00:36:51.882
molecules that were upregulated in the cancer cell or immune-excluded or

622
00:36:51.922 --> 00:36:52.762
immune-infiltrated.

623
00:36:54.562 --> 00:36:56.962
And what you're seeing here is the result from that experiment.

624
00:36:57.382 --> 00:37:01.042
On the right are transcripts that are enriching the cancer cells of

625
00:37:01.082 --> 00:37:04.312
immune-infiltrated tumors. Not surprisingly, we found chemokines,

626
00:37:04.402 --> 00:37:07.622
CXCL9, CXCL11, a few others, TAP1,

627
00:37:07.742 --> 00:37:10.742
TAP2, which was very rewarding to see that.

628
00:37:12.022 --> 00:37:15.742
But on the molecules enriching immune-excluded tumors, we actually

629
00:37:15.882 --> 00:37:19.222
rediscovered PLEC2G10, which you can see there, but also

630
00:37:19.282 --> 00:37:21.762
HER2, AXIN2, which was previously reported.

631
00:37:21.822 --> 00:37:23.762
So this actually made a lot of sense.

632
00:37:24.362 --> 00:37:27.852
Now, the most exciting thing is that we found all of these molecules or

633
00:37:27.942 --> 00:37:31.802
transcripts that have not been associated with immune exclusion or T

634
00:37:31.922 --> 00:37:35.282
cell migration that are enriched in immune-excluded tumors.

635
00:37:35.522 --> 00:37:39.122
And now I think we have a number of candidates that we can start looking at to

636
00:37:39.162 --> 00:37:41.782
potentially target even more immune excluders.

637
00:37:42.362 --> 00:37:46.262
So I'll show you two examples. This is called TCE1 and TCE3, both of which are

638
00:37:46.322 --> 00:37:48.942
secreted factors. We're prioritizing secreted factors.

639
00:37:49.442 --> 00:37:53.042
So we look at the literature, and T cell excluder one, you can see here, this is

640
00:37:53.262 --> 00:37:56.962
TCGA data, is mostly upregulated in lung squamous

641
00:37:57.002 --> 00:37:58.982
carcinoma, not so much in adenocarcinoma.

642
00:37:59.422 --> 00:38:03.062
It's negatively correlated with T cells in general and associated with worse

643
00:38:03.142 --> 00:38:05.542
outcomes, so pretty good so far.

644
00:38:06.422 --> 00:38:09.762
When we look across different tumor types, and lung is highlighted here with the

645
00:38:09.782 --> 00:38:13.602
bar, it's prominently upregulated in lung cancer, mostly, as

646
00:38:13.702 --> 00:38:17.262
I said, in squamous, but also in glioblastoma and also

647
00:38:17.562 --> 00:38:18.922
uterine carcinosarcoma and so on.

648
00:38:19.222 --> 00:38:23.202
So it could be that this mechanism, it's prominent in more than one

649
00:38:23.282 --> 00:38:25.542
tumor type and could potentially generalize.

650
00:38:27.182 --> 00:38:30.322
This is an example, the second example, to T cell excluder number three.

651
00:38:30.422 --> 00:38:34.362
You can see now this is high in adenocarcinoma, not so much in squamous, so it

652
00:38:34.402 --> 00:38:38.342
could be that different histologies are actually picking a different excluder

653
00:38:38.562 --> 00:38:42.232
mechanism. It's also negatively correlated with T cells and

654
00:38:42.302 --> 00:38:44.442
also somewhat associated with worse outcome.

655
00:38:45.082 --> 00:38:48.722
But now when we look at across different tumor types, we again see massive

656
00:38:48.762 --> 00:38:51.782
upregulation in lung adenocarcinoma relative to normal lung.

657
00:38:52.442 --> 00:38:55.682
And you can see again, colorectal cancer, very high relative to

658
00:38:55.702 --> 00:38:58.112
normal, pancreatic cancer, and others.

659
00:38:58.122 --> 00:39:02.042
So it could be that some of these excluders could affect other tumor types and

660
00:39:02.082 --> 00:39:06.002
not only lung. And now we're trying to figure out how it works.

661
00:39:06.102 --> 00:39:09.962
Now, to validate some of these excluders, because what I just showed you is just a

662
00:39:09.982 --> 00:39:13.122
correlation, we went back to a Boyden chamber assay of migration.

663
00:39:13.642 --> 00:39:16.582
So we basically took, again, the migration assay.

664
00:39:16.642 --> 00:39:20.502
We put CXCL11 on one side, we put the lymphocytes on the other

665
00:39:20.622 --> 00:39:24.202
side, and then we look at migration with or without treatment with this

666
00:39:24.662 --> 00:39:28.402
T cell excluder, candidate T cell excluders, and then we measure the cells by

667
00:39:28.442 --> 00:39:28.702
flow.

668
00:39:29.922 --> 00:39:33.211
And a long story short, you can see here in migration experiments that T cell

669
00:39:33.262 --> 00:39:37.202
excluder one and three significantly reduced the migration, and this is shown here.

670
00:39:38.042 --> 00:39:41.952
What was notorious, they did not change the expression of CXCR3,

671
00:39:42.022 --> 00:39:46.012
which is the main receptor for CXCL11, so it's not down-regulating

672
00:39:46.012 --> 00:39:49.802
the receptor, and it did not affect the viability of T cells, so we

673
00:39:49.822 --> 00:39:52.222
believe that this is a problem with migration.

674
00:39:52.482 --> 00:39:55.082
And now we're trying to find out the mechanism of that.

675
00:39:57.902 --> 00:39:59.142
So finally, I think a

676
00:40:00.062 --> 00:40:02.402
problem we face is how do we move this forward?

677
00:40:02.642 --> 00:40:06.051
Do we have the right models to ask questions about spatial orientation?

678
00:40:06.102 --> 00:40:10.092
If we do single-cell experiments, we cannot ask spatial questions, and in mice,

679
00:40:10.182 --> 00:40:14.042
it's very hard. So we had to create a model in which we could ask

680
00:40:14.082 --> 00:40:18.062
these questions. And to address this, we created these TAPEs,

681
00:40:18.142 --> 00:40:22.082
which stands for Tumor-Associated Primary Explants, where we actually take

682
00:40:22.602 --> 00:40:26.502
primary human tumors. We can grow them in a little dome of extracellular matrix

683
00:40:26.542 --> 00:40:30.432
and keep them alive for up to about 10 days, which is good enough to do

684
00:40:30.442 --> 00:40:34.382
pharmacodynamic analysis. These are pictures, and we generally also take

685
00:40:34.392 --> 00:40:38.262
non-tumor tissue. So we can actually keep the tissue intact, we

686
00:40:38.282 --> 00:40:41.462
can treat it with different things, and then ask questions about spatial

687
00:40:41.482 --> 00:40:44.162
distribution using the same assays that I just showed you.

688
00:40:45.532 --> 00:40:48.832
This is an example of the model where you can see in this case, it's a positive

689
00:40:48.842 --> 00:40:52.262
control. We treat it or not with interleukin-2, which is expected to

690
00:40:52.302 --> 00:40:55.142
increase CD4 and CD8 T cell proliferation.

691
00:40:56.002 --> 00:40:59.102
And these are different days, so day zero, three, five, up to seven.

692
00:40:59.722 --> 00:41:01.082
And you can see that we can detect

693
00:41:01.982 --> 00:41:05.602
expansion of CD4s and CD8s, and we can resolve them, the tumor and stroma.

694
00:41:05.662 --> 00:41:09.482
This is all done using FFPE preparation from these specimens.

695
00:41:09.922 --> 00:41:13.542
And we have tested a number of drugs at this point in the lab, bispecific

696
00:41:13.602 --> 00:41:17.522
antibodies, antibody-drug conjugates, immunomodulatory drugs, and I think we've got

697
00:41:17.642 --> 00:41:19.642
a good idea of how to interrogate the model.

698
00:41:20.982 --> 00:41:24.692
The most interesting thing is that because PLEC2G10 was secreted, we were afraid

699
00:41:24.722 --> 00:41:28.272
that we may not be able to target, but you can see these are three independent

700
00:41:28.272 --> 00:41:32.222
tumors from different patients, and we can find PLEC2G10 retained in the

701
